uì™T<?php exit; ?>a:1:{s:7:"content";O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:4:"3619";s:11:"post_author";s:2:"11";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2014-07-05 20:48:13";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2014-07-05 20:48:13";s:12:"post_content";s:3890:"The films of Wes Anderson are recognizable for his centered shots, surrealist imagery in motion with the help of visual effects, and for this set it was a collaboration with the firm Look Effects which weâ€™ll explore in the following. A first look at this film was to distinguish the characteristic color of the Grand Budapest Hotel - Its unique texture and photographic scenery, decorative elements, and retro look dating from pre world war II.

<a href="http://www.vjsmag.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/vjs-magazine-visual-effects-for-wes-andersons-the-grand-budapest-hotel-2.jpg"><img class="alignnone" src="http://www.vjsmag.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/vjs-magazine-visual-effects-for-wes-andersons-the-grand-budapest-hotel-2-300x219.jpg" alt="vjs-magazine-visual-effects-for-wes-andersons-the-grand-budapest-hotel-2" /></a>

The recording team traveled around Europe, looking for the perfect hotel, but did not find what they were looking for. What they located was an old commercial center which dated from early 20th century, and made a unique renaissance architecture and interior decoration to create the grand hotel. - Red and green carpets, distinctive rounded roof and arcs with a similar classical exterior corners and flooring. But much of it, is trompe lâ€™oeil and made with special effects, most of the art deco details is conceptualized and rendered. And the final touch, adding layer after layer, until achieving the perfect shade of color and atmosphere the director wanted to get.
Great attention to details, the dresses, the main actors and extras were key. The color palette was meticulous: contrast and light to provoke moods according the situation.

<a href="http://www.vjsmag.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/vjs-magazine-visual-effects-for-wes-andersons-the-grand-budapest-hotel-5.jpg"><img class="alignnone" src="http://www.vjsmag.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/vjs-magazine-visual-effects-for-wes-andersons-the-grand-budapest-hotel-5-150x150.jpg" alt="vjs-magazine-visual-effects-for-wes-andersons-the-grand-budapest-hotel-5" /></a> <a href="http://www.vjsmag.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/vjs-magazine-visual-effects-for-wes-andersons-the-grand-budapest-hotel-4.jpg"><img class="alignnone" src="http://www.vjsmag.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/vjs-magazine-visual-effects-for-wes-andersons-the-grand-budapest-hotel-4-150x150.jpg" alt="The Grand Budapest Hotel - 64th Berlin Film Festival" /></a>

Look Effects, visual art company, produced the VFX for Wes Anderson. The green screen work, the way all the miniature set pieces are integrated into establishing and compositing shot.
The air trams were miniatures and the Hotel as well, assembled miniatures, stop-motion animation, background environments and atmospherics effects for the sequences. Layer after layer of work to get the perfect tone, concept from an oil painting photographed and creating these matte paintings.

<img class="alignnone" src="http://www.vjsmag.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/vjs-magazine-visual-effects-for-wes-andersons-the-grand-budapest-hotel-3.jpg" alt="vjs-magazine-visual-effects-for-wes-andersons-the-grand-budapest-hotel-3" />

Complex multi-step process of building actions that filled out numerous scenes shot in front of a green screen and three-dimensional modeling. The precision of the shading, lighting, color and texture.
The firm known as Look Effects played a major role in finding the balance between the real look and the charm of the miniature crucial for the filmâ€™s atmosphere. Part of their work was also: adjust motion blur, trailing, add snow and mist flying past the camera to make it feel like it is part of the environment.

